#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:1
msgid "The Code Generator: rustc-codegen-cuda"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:3
msgid ""
"Every Rust program eventually reaches the codegen backend -- the part of the "
"compiler that turns optimized MIR into machine code. Normally, that backend "
"is LLVM. cuda-oxide swaps in its own backend, `rustc-codegen-cuda`, which "
"intercepts this process to extract device code and route it through the cuda-"
"oxide pipeline before handing everything else back to LLVM as if nothing "
"happened."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:10
msgid ""
"This page explains how that backend loads, what it does when rustc calls it, "
"and how it finds every function that belongs on the GPU."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:15
msgid "How rustc Loads a Custom Backend"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:17
msgid "rustc has a flag most people never see:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:19
msgid "rustc -Z codegen-backend=path/to/libfoo.so\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:23
msgid "When you pass this flag, rustc does the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:25
msgid "Calls `dlopen` on the shared library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:26
msgid "Calls `dlsym(\"__rustc_codegen_backend\")` to find the entry point."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:27
msgid "Expects that function to return a `Box<dyn CodegenBackend>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:29
msgid ""
"That's it. No plugin registry, no config files, no handshake protocol. One "
"symbol, one trait object, and you own the codegen pipeline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:32
msgid "cuda-oxide provides this entry point:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:34
msgid ""
"#[unsafe(no_mangle)]\n"
"pub fn __rustc_codegen_backend() -> Box<dyn CodegenBackend> {\n"
"    let config = CudaCodegenConfig::from_env();\n"
"    let llvm_backend = rustc_codegen_llvm::LlvmCodegenBackend::new();\n"
"    Box::new(CudaCodegenBackend { config, llvm_backend })\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:43
msgid ""
"Two things happen here. First, `CudaCodegenConfig::from_env()` reads "
"environment variables (`CUDA_OXIDE_VERBOSE`, `CUDA_OXIDE_DUMP_MIR`, and "
"friends -- see {ref}`Environment Variables <rustc-codegen-environment-"
"variables>` below) to configure the backend's behavior. Second, it creates "
"the standard LLVM backend and stores it inside the `CudaCodegenBackend`. "
"This is the wrapping pattern that makes the whole architecture work: cuda-"
"oxide does not *replace* the LLVM backend, it *wraps* it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:53
msgid ""
"`cargo oxide build` sets the `-Z codegen-backend` flag for you. You never "
"need to type the `dlopen` incantation yourself unless you enjoy that sort of "
"thing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:59
msgid "The Intercept: codegen_crate()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:61
msgid ""
"The `CodegenBackend` trait has several methods, but the one that matters is "
"`codegen_crate(tcx)`. This is where rustc hands over the entire typed, "
"borrow-checked, monomorphized crate and says \"make this into machine code.\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:65
msgid ""
"When rustc calls `CudaCodegenBackend::codegen_crate(tcx)`, here is what "
"happens:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:68
msgid "Step 1: Collect Monomorphized Items"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:70
msgid "let (items, cgus) = tcx.collect_and_partition_mono_items(());\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:74
msgid ""
"This gives us every monomorphized function in the crate, grouped into "
"**codegen units** (CGUs). A CGU is rustc's unit of parallel code generation "
"-- think of it as a bucket of functions that will become one object file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:78
msgid "Step 2: Scan for Device Entry Points"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:80
msgid ""
"The backend iterates over every function in every CGU and checks for the "
"magic name prefixes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:83
msgid "`cuda_oxide_kernel_<hash>_` -- set by `#[kernel]`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:84
msgid "`cuda_oxide_device_<hash>_` -- set by `#[device]`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:86
msgid ""
"These prefixes are how the proc macros communicate with the backend. There "
"is no special attribute metadata, no side channel -- just a name that stands "
"out in a crowd. The exact prefix strings (and the helpers that match and "
"strip them) live in the workspace-internal `reserved-oxide-symbols` crate; "
"both the macro side and the collector side import from there so the contract "
"stays in one place. The 8-hex-char `<hash>` makes accidental collisions "
"effectively impossible: nobody writes `cuda_oxide_kernel_246e25db_foo` by "
"accident."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:94
msgid "Step 3: If Device Code Found, Build and Compile"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:96
msgid ""
"If any kernel or device function is found, two things happen in sequence:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:98
msgid ""
"**a) Collect the device call graph.** `collector::"
"collect_device_functions()` performs a breadth-first walk from every kernel "
"entry point, discovering all functions that transitively get called from "
"device code. More on this in {ref}`Device Function Collection <rustc-codegen-"
"device-function-collection>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:104
msgid ""
"**b) Generate device code.** `device_codegen::generate_device_code()` "
"bridges the collected functions to stable MIR and runs the full cuda-oxide "
"pipeline (`dialect-mir` -> `mem2reg` -> annotated loop unroll -> LLVM "
"dialect -> `.ll` -> PTX)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:109
msgid "Step 4: Always Compile Host Code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:111
msgid "Regardless of whether device code was found:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:113
msgid "self.llvm_backend.codegen_crate(tcx)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:117
msgid ""
"The wrapped LLVM backend compiles all the host code -- `main()`, your CLI "
"parser, your async runtime, everything. The device pipeline is a side quest; "
"the host pipeline always runs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:121
msgid "The Other Trait Methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:123
msgid ""
"The `CodegenBackend` trait also requires `join_codegen()` and `link()`. "
"These handle waiting for parallel codegen threads and invoking the linker, "
"respectively. In cuda-oxide, both are pure delegation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:127
msgid ""
"fn join_codegen(&self, ongoing: Box<dyn Any>, sess: &Session) -> ... {\n"
"    self.llvm_backend.join_codegen(ongoing, sess)\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"fn link(&self, sess: &Session, codegen: ..., outputs: &OutputFilenames) -"
"> ... {\n"
"    self.llvm_backend.link(sess, codegen, outputs)\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:137
msgid ""
"No interception, no modification. The LLVM backend handles linking exactly "
"as it normally would."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:141
msgid ""
"For most crates in the dependency tree -- `core`, `cuda-core`, random "
"utility crates -- no kernels are found and the backend just delegates to "
"LLVM. The device pipeline only activates for the crate that actually "
"contains a `#[kernel]` function. For a typical project, that means one crate "
"out of dozens triggers device compilation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:152
msgid "Device Function Collection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:154
msgid ""
"Finding kernel entry points is the easy part. The hard part is figuring out "
"*everything else* those kernels call. A kernel might call a helper, which "
"calls a `cuda-device` intrinsic, which calls a `core` math function -- and "
"all of those need to end up in the PTX."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:159
msgid ""
"The `collector` module handles this with a breadth-first traversal of the "
"MIR call graph."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:162
msgid "The Worklist Algorithm"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:164
msgid ""
"worklist = [all kernel entry points]\n"
"visited  = {}\n"
"collected = []\n"
"\n"
"while worklist is not empty:\n"
"    fn = worklist.pop()\n"
"    if fn in visited: continue\n"
"    visited.add(fn)\n"
"\n"
"    mir = tcx.instance_mir(fn)\n"
"    collected.push(fn)\n"
"\n"
"    for basic_block in mir:\n"
"        for terminator in [Call, Drop]:\n"
"            callee = resolve_callee(terminator)\n"
"            if should_collect(callee):\n"
"                worklist.push(callee)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:184
msgid ""
"For each function, the collector retrieves its MIR via `tcx.instance_mir()`, "
"then scans every basic block's terminator. `Call` and `Drop` terminators "
"reference callees, which get added to the worklist if they pass the crate "
"filtering rules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:189
msgid "The output is a `Vec<CollectedFunction>`, where each entry carries:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:191
msgid ""
"The monomorphized `Instance` (the fully resolved, generic-free function)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:192
msgid "An `is_kernel` flag (for marking GPU entry points in the PTX metadata)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:193
msgid "The `export_name` (the symbol name visible in the final PTX)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:195
msgid "Export Names and FQDN Alignment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:197
msgid ""
"The collector must produce export names that match what the MIR translator "
"generates for call targets. Both sides use **fully qualified domain names "
"(FQDNs)** -- for example, `helper_fn::"
"cuda_oxide_device_<hash>_vecadd_device` rather than bare `vecadd_device`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:202
msgid ""
"The `rustc_public` API's `CrateDef::name()` returns FQDNs including the "
"crate name. On the collector side, `def_path_str()` omits the crate name for "
"local items, so a small helper (`fqdn()`) prepends it for local definitions "
"to produce the same string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:207
msgid ""
"During lowering, `::` is converted to `__` on both the definition and call "
"sides, producing valid LLVM/PTX identifiers (e.g., "
"`helper_fn__vecadd_device`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:210
msgid ""
"For generic or complex names (angle brackets, closures), the mangled symbol "
"name is used instead -- this is unique and already a valid identifier."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:213
msgid ""
"Kernel entry points follow a separate path: `compute_kernel_export_name` "
"takes the `#[kernel]` macro's base name and, for generic and closure- "
"generic instantiations, appends `_TID_<hex32>` where `<hex32>` is rustc's "
"128-bit type-id hash of the concrete generated kernel function item. That "
"`FnDef` contains ordered type and const arguments. The host launcher "
"computes the same hash through the `core::intrinsics::type_id` intrinsic "
"(wrapped by `cuda_host::type_id_u128_of_val`), so both sides agree byte-for-"
"byte within one unified build. Non-generic kernels keep their bare base name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:224
msgid ""
"This FQDN alignment strategy will be replaced by pliron's `Legaliser` when "
"the framework is upgraded. The `Legaliser` provides systematic name "
"sanitization with collision detection, making manual `::` to `__` "
"replacement unnecessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:230
msgid "Crate Filtering Rules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:232
msgid ""
"Not every function in the dependency tree belongs on a GPU. The collector "
"enforces rules about which crates are allowed in device code:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "Crate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "Status"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "Local crate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "Allowed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "Your kernel code"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "`cuda_device`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "GPU intrinsics (stubs filtered -- see below)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "`core`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "`no_std` standard library"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "Other `no_std` crates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "Any crate in the dependency tree"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "`std`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "**Forbidden**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "Compile-time error"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "`alloc`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "Allowed (if GPU allocator)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:223
msgid "Experimental"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:244
msgid ""
"The rule is simple: if a crate could conceivably run on a GPU (no OS "
"dependencies, no file I/O, no networking), it is allowed. If it drags in "
"`std`, it is not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:248
msgid "Error Messages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:250
msgid ""
"When someone accidentally tries to use `std` in device code -- perhaps a "
"stray `println!` left over from debugging -- the collector produces a clear "
"error instead of letting the build fail with an inscrutable PTX assembler "
"message three stages later:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:255
msgid ""
"CUDA-OXIDE: FORBIDDEN CRATE IN DEVICE CODE\n"
"Device code calls: std::io::_print\n"
"From crate: 'std'\n"
"Only these crates are allowed in device code:\n"
"  - Local crate (your kernel code)\n"
"  - cuda_device (GPU intrinsics)\n"
"  - core (no_std standard library)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:265
msgid ""
"This is one of the advantages of catching the problem at the call graph "
"level rather than hoping LLVM will produce a useful diagnostic. (It won't.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:268
msgid "Intrinsic Stub Filtering"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:270
msgid ""
"`cuda_device` contains functions like `threadIdx_x()` whose bodies are just "
"`unreachable!()`. These are stubs -- placeholders that exist so rustc can "
"type-check device code, but they are never meant to be compiled as real "
"functions. They get replaced by `dialect-nvvm` operations later in the "
"pipeline (for instance, `threadIdx_x()` becomes `nvvm.read_ptx_sreg_tid_x`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:276
msgid ""
"The collector recognizes these stubs -- they come from `cuda_device` and "
"have no meaningful MIR beyond a single `unreachable` terminator -- and skips "
"them. If you are wondering \"but if the body is `unreachable!()`, won't that "
"panic at runtime?\": no, because `mir-importer` replaces calls to these "
"functions with the corresponding GPU hardware instructions before any code "
"generation happens. The stub body never executes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:285
msgid "Cross-Crate Device Compilation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:287
msgid ""
"Here is a question that sounds simple until you think about it: when you "
"call `cuda_device::thread::index_1d()` from a kernel, how does the compiler "
"get that function's MIR? Your crate does not have its source code. "
"`cuda_device` was compiled hours ago, possibly by a different machine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:292
msgid "The answer lies in how rustc stores metadata."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:294
msgid "The .rlib Flow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:296
msgid ""
"When rustc compiles `cuda_device`, there are no `#[kernel]` functions in "
"that crate. The cuda-oxide backend finds nothing to intercept and delegates "
"entirely to LLVM. The output is a standard `.rlib` archive containing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:300
msgid "**Compiled machine code** -- the host-side object file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:301
msgid ""
"**`.rmeta` metadata blob** -- type information, trait impls, and crucially, "
"**serialized optimized MIR** for certain functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:304
msgid ""
"Later, when you compile your `vecadd` crate, the collector finds a kernel "
"entry point and starts the BFS walk. It encounters a call to `cuda_device::"
"thread::index_1d()`. At this point, `tcx.instance_mir()` reaches into "
"`cuda_device`'s `.rmeta` blob and retrieves the function's MIR -- fully "
"optimized, monomorphized, ready to translate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:314
msgid ""
"Cross-crate device compilation. Phase 1 compiles cuda_device into an .rlib "
"with serialized MIR in its .rmeta blob. Phase 2 compiles vecadd -- the "
"collector finds a kernel, BFS walks into cuda_device, reads the MIR from ."
"rmeta, and compiles everything to PTX."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:320
msgid ""
"Device code from dependency crates is compiled to PTX **lazily** -- only "
"when a kernel in your crate transitively references it. If you never call a "
"function, it never ends up in the PTX, even if it exists in the dependency."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:324
msgid "Which Functions Get Their MIR Encoded in .rmeta?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:326
msgid ""
"Not every function's MIR survives into the `.rmeta` blob. rustc has rules "
"about what gets serialized:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:310
msgid "Category"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:310
msgid "Why it's serialized"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:310
msgid "Generic functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:310
msgid "Must be monomorphized downstream -- the MIR is the \"template\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:310
msgid "`#[inline]` functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:310
msgid "Explicitly requested for cross-crate inlining"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:310
msgid "`#[inline(always)]` functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:310
msgid "Same, but more insistent about it"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:310
msgid "Small leaf functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:310
msgid "Heuristic: no calls, few statements -- cheap to inline"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:336
msgid ""
"Most `cuda_device` functions fall into at least one of these categories. GPU "
"intrinsics are small. Helper functions are `#[inline]`. Generic functions "
"over element types are, well, generic. The result is that virtually all "
"device-side library code has its MIR available for cross-crate compilation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:342
msgid ""
"This is not a cuda-oxide feature -- it is standard rustc behavior, designed "
"to support cross-crate inlining and generic instantiation. cuda-oxide just "
"happens to benefit enormously from it, since the same mechanism that lets "
"rustc inline a `Vec::push` call across crates also lets us compile a "
"`cuda_device::thread::index_1d()` call to PTX."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:351
msgid "The Bridge to Stable MIR"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:353
msgid ""
"After the collector finishes, we have a `Vec<CollectedFunction>` containing "
"every device function as an internal rustc `Instance`. But `mir-importer` "
"does not speak rustc internals -- it works with the stable MIR API provided "
"by `rustc_public`. We need a bridge."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:358
msgid "The `device_codegen` module handles the translation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:360
msgid ""
"rustc_internal::run(tcx, || {\n"
"    let stable_instances: Vec<_> = collected\n"
"        .iter()\n"
"        .map(|f| rustc_internal::stable(f.instance))\n"
"        .collect();\n"
"    mir_importer::run_pipeline(&stable_instances, &config)\n"
"})\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:370
msgid "Two things are happening here:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:372
msgid ""
"**`rustc_internal::run(tcx, || { ... })`** sets up the thread-local context "
"that `rustc_public` requires. Inside this closure, stable MIR queries work. "
"Outside it, they would panic -- the stable API needs access to the compiler "
"session, and this function provides it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:377
msgid ""
"**`rustc_internal::stable(f.instance)`** converts each internal "
"`rustc_middle::ty::Instance` to its stable equivalent, `stable_mir::mir::"
"mono::Instance`. This is a one-way conversion -- internal types can become "
"stable types, but not the other way around."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:382
msgid ""
"Once the conversion is done, `mir_importer::run_pipeline()` takes over. It "
"reads the stable MIR for each instance, translates it into pliron's MIR "
"dialect, and runs the full lowering pipeline through to PTX. That process is "
"covered in [The MIR Importer](mir-importer.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:391
msgid "Environment Variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:393
msgid ""
"`CudaCodegenConfig::from_env()` reads the following environment variables to "
"control the backend's behavior. All are optional -- the defaults produce a "
"quiet, production-oriented build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:341
msgid "Variable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:341
msgid "Effect"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/rustc-codegen-cuda.md:341
msgid "`CUDA_OXIDE_VERBOSE`"
msgstr ""

